Title:
Detecting Malicious Use of Net – Part 2

Type:
Blog Post

Short Summary (4–8 sentences max):
This post continues F-Secure’s analysis of how attackers abuse the Windows `net.exe`/`net1.exe` utilities (“living off the land”) for discovery and lateral movement preparation. It focuses on detection opportunities that distinguish legitimate administrative usage from attacker tradecraft by correlating process execution context, command-line patterns, and follow-on activity. The article discusses telemetry sources (e.g., Windows event logs/Sysmon/EDR) and how to build higher-fidelity detections around `net` commands used for user/group enumeration, domain queries, and share/session inspection. It emphasizes behavioral detection and correlation rather than simple string-matching, to reduce false positives in enterprise environments. This is primarily useful for Blue Teams and detection engineers, but also helps red teamers understand what `net` usage is likely to trigger alerts. It’s interesting because `net` is ubiquitous and noisy, so practical detection guidance requires careful context and chaining.

Technical Focus:
- Windows `net.exe` / `net1.exe` LOLBin abuse
- Command-line analytics and suspicious argument patterns
- Process ancestry/parent-child relationships (e.g., Office → cmd → net)
- Log/telemetry correlation (Windows Security logs, Sysmon, EDR)
- Discovery and enumeration tradecraft in AD environments
- Detection engineering and false-positive reduction

Use Cases:
- Build SIEM/EDR detections for suspicious `net` command execution
- Hunt for AD discovery activity preceding credential theft or lateral movement
- Create correlation rules tying `net` usage to unusual parent processes or remote execution
- Baseline legitimate admin `net` usage to tune alert thresholds
- Red-team validation of defensive coverage for common enumeration commands

Keywords:
net.exe, net1.exe, Windows LOLBins, living-off-the-land, command-line detection, process lineage, Sysmon, Windows Security Event Log, SIEM, EDR telemetry, Active Directory discovery, user enumeration, group enumeration, domain reconnaissance, share enumeration, session enumeration, detection engineering, threat hunting, false positives